      Noncompetes
   =20
 =20
Is there still=C2=A0gardening leave? Yesterday, the US Federal Trade Commis=
sion voted to ban employee noncompete agreements in the US.
  [1]
=C2=A0Future noncompetes are banned; existing noncompetes are enforceable o=
nly for senior executives.
  [2]
=C2=A0The rule goes into effect in six months, and there will definitely be=
 lawsuits to block it.=C2=A0In the final rule document, the FTC notes that =
=E2=80=9Cemployers subject even middle-income and low-wage workers to nonco=
mpetes on a widespread basis,=E2=80=9D but of course noncompetes are also c=
ommon for high-income workers in the financial industry. There, noncompetes=
 are not entirely a bad thing for workers. =E2=80=9CAll I know is power-was=
hing and these business owners all want me to sign a noncompete clause,=E2=
=80=9D says a power-washer cited by the FTC. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s one big =
circle of wealthy business owners keeping the little man down.=E2=80=9D But=
 on the r/quant Reddit board=C2=A0feelings are mixed, and you can find post=
s saying things like=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwould suck if this means no garden leave=
 is available anymore.=E2=80=9D In the financial industry, there is a commo=
n norm that, if you leave a job, you are not allowed to work for a competit=
or for some period of months or years, during which you are still paid by y=
our old employer. This makes it harder for you to get a new job and=C2=A0re=
duces your negotiating leverage at your current job, and if you=C2=A0do=C2=
=A0leave, the enforced time off devalues your skills and holds back your ca=
reer. On the other hand: year-long vacation! There are probably some people=
 who structure their financial careers around maximizing gardening leave. D=
id the FTC end that?I don=E2=80=99t think so, though it=E2=80=99s a little =
unclear. There are roughly four ways that financial firms typically deter p=
eople from leaving for competitors:=09Noncompetes: When you start your job,=
 you sign a contract promising not to work for a competitor for, say, six m=
onths
  [3]
=C2=A0after you quit.=09Notice periods: When you start your job, you sign a=
 contract saying that, if you want to quit, you have to give six months=E2=
=80=99 advance notice. Then, when you give notice, your employer says =E2=
=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t even bother coming to the office anymore, and we=E2=80=
=99re cutting you off email, but you still work for us so you can=E2=80=99t=
 work for a competitor.=E2=80=9D And they keep paying you. (Often your base=
 salary but not your bonus.)=09Deferred comp: Each year, your employer pays=
 you some cash and also some deferred pay, cash or stock or options or carr=
y that they hold onto for you and promise to deliver to you at some later d=
ate. The terms of the deferred pay say that you can forfeit it in certain c=
ircumstances. For instance, if you do a crime, or lose a bunch of money for=
 the firm, they can claw back deferred pay that you earned in previous year=
s. Often, if you leave the firm for a competitor, they can also claw it bac=
k.=09Nondisclosure agreements (NDAs): When you start your job, you sign a c=
ontract saying that all of the stuff you learn and do at the job is secret =
and belongs to your employer, and that you are not allowed to disclose it t=
o anyone else. And then when you quit, they say =E2=80=9Cjust so you know, =
if you go work at a competitor, we=E2=80=99ll know that you=E2=80=99re usin=
g our secrets, and we=E2=80=99ll sue you.=E2=80=9DThe new FTC rule pretty c=
learly bans No. 1, the explicit noncompete. But No. 2 is a common way to do=
 gardening leave, and I think it still works? The FTC says:With respect to =
garden leave agreements, as noted previously, commenters used the term =E2=
=80=9Cgarden leave=E2=80=9D to refer to a wide variety of agreements. =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0However, the Commission notes that an agreement whereby the wor=
ker is still employed and receiving the same total annual compensation and =
benefits on a pro rata basis would not be a non-compete clause under the de=
finition, because such an agreement is not a post-employment restriction. I=
nstead, the worker continues to be employed, even though the worker=E2=80=
=99s job duties or access to colleagues or the workplace may be significant=
ly or entirely curtailed. Furthermore, where a worker does not meet a condi=
tion to earn a particular aspect of their expected compensation, like a pre=
requisite for a bonus, the Commission would still consider the arrangement =
=E2=80=9Cgarden leave=E2=80=9D that is not a non-compete clause under this =
final rule even if the employer did not pay the bonus or other expected com=
pensation.=C2=A0That leaves some ambiguity about bonuses: Your gardening le=
ave has to provide =E2=80=9Cthe same total annual compensation=E2=80=9D as =
your regular job for it to be allowed, but if you do not meet =E2=80=9Ca pr=
erequisite for a bonus,=E2=80=9D they don=E2=80=99t have to pay you the bon=
us. Presumably showing up to the office is a prerequisite for your bonus, s=
o I=C2=A0think=C2=A0this says that gardening leave is still allowed as long=
 as you are getting your normal base salary, which can be quite a lot lower=
 than your normal=C2=A0total annual compensation.The rule=C2=A0also seems t=
o ban=C2=A0No. 3, the clawback of deferred compensation for workers who lea=
ve for competitors. The rule defines a =E2=80=9Cnon-compete clause=E2=80=9D=
 to include =E2=80=9Ca term or condition of employment that prohibits a wor=
ker from,=C2=A0penalizes a worker for, or functions to prevent a worker fro=
m =E2=80=A6=C2=A0seeking or accepting work=E2=80=9D at a competitor (emphas=
is added). The FTC says:Another example of a term that =E2=80=9Cpenalizes=
=E2=80=9D a worker ... is an agreement that extinguishes a person=E2=80=99s=
 obligation to provide promised compensation or to pay benefits as a result=
 of a worker seeking or accepting other work or starting a business after t=
hey leave their job. One example of such an agreement is a forfeiture-for-c=
ompetition clause, which, similar to the agreement with liquidated damages =
described previously, imposes adverse financial consequences on a former em=
ployee as a result of the termination of an employment relationship, expres=
sly conditioned on the employee seeking or accepting other work or starting=
 a business=C2=A0after their employment ends.Here too there is some ambigui=
ty. The way deferred compensation works at some financial firms is that you=
 lose your unvested compensation if you leave for=C2=A0any=C2=A0reason, whe=
ther or not you are going to a competitor. But the firm will, as a matter o=
f informal policy, let you keep that compensation if you leave for certain=
=C2=A0good=C2=A0reasons: if you=E2=80=99ve been there a long time and are r=
etiring, say, or you=E2=80=99re going into public service or charity work o=
r to work at a big client. (Goldman Sachs Group Inc. had some controversy a=
 while back for tightening up this policy.) Perhaps an employment contract =
that says =E2=80=9Cwe will take back all your deferred compensation if you =
leave for any reason,=E2=80=9D combined with a winking understanding that a=
ctually you can keep it as long as you don=E2=80=99t leave for a competitor=
, is a way to implement a noncompete under the FTC=E2=80=99s rules.(Inciden=
tally, I mentioned Goldman,=C2=A0but in fact the rule seems=C2=A0not=C2=A0t=
o apply to banks. Sifma, the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Asso=
ciation, in commenting on the proposed rules, =E2=80=9Cwarned that banks an=
