gy that is so secret that it can=E2=80=99t even name the country where it t=
rades options (it=E2=80=99s India). Millennium, and the employees, argue: L=
ook, they are options traders, they=E2=80=99ve learned how to trade options=
, those are generally applicable skills that transfer, and if they=E2=80=99=
re using those skills to trade options at Millennium then that=E2=80=99s fi=
ne. Millennium=E2=80=99s lawyer =E2=80=9Ccompared the two traders to gold m=
iners who =E2=80=98really know how to use a pickax.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DThat s=
ort of lawsuit is unusual, though not unheard-of. (Most of the cases involv=
e alleged theft of code, not copying a discretionary trading strategy.) One=
 reason these lawsuits are unusual is=C2=A0because of noncompetes=C2=A0(and=
 gardening leave). If you work at a financial firm doing secret stuff, and =
you leave for a competitor, and you have to=C2=A0wait a year=C2=A0before st=
arting at the competitor, most of the secret stuff will have lost its value=
