I used to be a convertible-bonds investment banker, and there=E2=80=99s a s=
tandard story about the payout of convertible debt. If you buy a convertibl=
e bond and the company does very well, you will make a lot of money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0your bond will convert into common stock and share in the upside =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0though less than if you had just bought stock. If the compan=
y does poorly, you will probably get your money back, or at least be toward=
 the front of the line for getting your money back, which is much better th=
an the common stockholders will do. Convertibles share in the upside of sto=
ck, but with less downside.That=E2=80=99s a nice pitch, but=C2=A0I have nev=
er seen this fact pattern before:[Software startup Toptal LLC] raised early=
 funding from Andreessen Horowitz and individuals like Ryan Rockefeller, an=
d later raised $1 million more from [investor Denis] Grosz. Grosz=E2=80=99s=
 investments came in the form of debt =E2=80=94 a convertible note that con=
verts to equity when a startup raises more cash. Grosz=E2=80=99s deal inclu=
ded rights to around 10% of the company after its first equity financing. B=
ut Grosz didn=E2=80=99t get his stake: Toptal never raised more equity, and=
 a conversion never happened. ...Today, 10% of Toptal likely would be worth=
 a lot more than $1 million. According to [Toptal founder Taso] Du Val, Top=
tal had $270 million in revenue in 2022, the most recent audited numbers av=
ailable. In his countersuit, Grosz estimated that Toptal could be valued at=
 more than $1 billion.Grosz could still see an equity conversion =E2=80=94 =
Toptal raising more money would trigger one =E2=80=94 but Du Val said in an=
 interview that it doesn=E2=80=99t make sense, in part due to tax reasons, =
to pursue that now.That is: Grosz=E2=80=99s debt shared in the equity upsid=
e,=C2=A0if the company raised more equity. The ordinary upside case for a S=
ilicon Valley startup is something like =E2=80=9Cthe company does well, and=
 it is able to=C2=A0raise more money at a higher valuation on its way to an=
 initial public offering.=E2=80=9D That would be a great story for Grosz=E2=
=80=99s convertible. And that is the story everyone implicitly assumes, whi=
ch is why the document was written that way.But another entirely possible u=
pside case is =E2=80=9Cthe company does well, it brings in tons of money, t=
hat money funds all of its business needs and also its founder=E2=80=99s li=
festyle, it never needs to raise equity again, and, given the choice of kee=
ping a $1 million convertible bond outstanding or converting it into $100 m=
illion of equity, it takes the cheaper choice.=E2=80=9D Of course the cheap=
er choice is really to pay the bond back at par. =E2=80=9CToptal tried to p=
ay it back with interest in March 2020, according to his and Toptal=E2=80=
=99s suits, but Grosz rejected the attempt.=E2=80=9D Reasonable, on both si=
des!
