There is a form of argument, in crypto, that is like: =E2=80=9CThis token c=
osts $10. If you buy a token and hold it, it will turn into six tokens. If =
each of those tokens is still worth $10, you will have turned $10 into $60.=
=E2=80=9D This had an immense vogue for a while, but it was always easy to =
see the flaw in the argument. The flaw was: Why would multiplying the suppl=
y of an arbitrary electronic token by six multiply its total value by six? =
If everyone had one Meaningless Token, and then by operation of a computer =
everyone instead has=C2=A0six Meaningless Tokens, how has their actual weal=
th=C2=A0increased?With apartments in China the situation is a bit more ambi=
guous. Here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal story about how the Chinese rea=
l estate industry seems to have operated, for a while, by turning each=C2=
=A0rural home into six rural homes:It seemed to be a great deal at the time=
: Swap an aging townhouse and a small piece of farmland for five apartments=
 and two stores.Bella Zhao=E2=80=99s family grabbed that offer in 2009, whe=
n property developers led by Wanda Group moved into their sparse, snow-capp=
ed village in China=E2=80=99s northeastern Jilin province. Wanda planned to=
