tters worse, villagers who traded their homes with developers, often for se=
veral new apartments, are adding to the wall of potential supply, said Liu =
Yuan, head of property research at Centaline.=E2=80=9CIt is impossible to s=
ell at a decent price,=E2=80=9D said a homeowner in Nanjing, who owns eight=
 properties with her husband and parents, five of which were compensation f=
or relocating.On the one hand, right, if you multiply the supply of apartme=
nts by six, and change nothing else (population, tourism, etc.), then the p=
rice of those apartments is going to go down. On the other hand, now you ha=
ve more room? =E2=80=9CPerhaps two of the apartments will be occupied by hi=
s relatives,=E2=80=9D says a guy in Henan who traded a house for six apartm=
ents, though=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe rest will sit empty.=E2=80=9D Possibly that =
is an increase in wealth?
