  [1] I say =E2=80=9Cemployee noncompete agreements=E2=80=9D because there=
=E2=80=99s an exception for noncompetes in connection with the sale of a bu=
siness.


  [2] =E2=80=9CThe final rule defines senior executives as workers earning =
more than $151,164 annually and who are in policy-making positions,=E2=80=
=9D says the FTC. In many uses, =E2=80=9Csenior executive=E2=80=9D can turn=
 out to mean =E2=80=9Ceveryone employed in a professional role at a financi=
al-services firm,=E2=80=9D but I don=E2=80=99t think it means that here. He=
re I think it means something close to =E2=80=9Cno, actually, a senior exec=
utive.=E2=80=9D The final rule document says that noncompetes can=E2=80=99t=
 be enforced against =E2=80=9Crelatively higher paid or highly skilled work=
ers who lack policy-making authority,=E2=80=9D because they =E2=80=9Care un=
likely to have engaged in bargaining in connection with non-competes.=E2=80=
=9D And: =E2=80=9CFor a worker to be a senior executive, in addition to mee=
ting the compensation threshold, the worker must be at the level of a presi=
dent, chief executive officer or the equivalent, officer (defined in =C2=A7=
 910.1), or in a position that has similar authority to a president or offi=
cer.=E2=80=9D


  [3] As a relatively junior investment banker, my experience of this was a=
 few months. In high-end buy-side jobs, one or two-year noncompetes are not=
 uncommon.


  [4] From Sifma=E2=80=99s comment letter: =E2=80=9CAs a result of the Comm=
ission=E2=80=99s limited jurisdiction, it will create an uneven playing fie=
ld between businesses subject to the Commission=E2=80=99s limited jurisdict=
ion and their competitors that lie outside of that jurisdiction.=E2=80=9D A=
 footnote adds: =E2=80=9CSpecifically, the Commission lacks jurisdiction ov=
er banks, savings and loan institutions, federal credit unions, common carr=
iers, air carriers and foreign air carriers, non-profit organizations, pers=
ons subject to the Packers and Stockyards Act of 1921, and certain state an=
d local government entities protected by the state action doctrine.=E2=80=
=9D


  [5] Don=E2=80=99t take this too literally. Evercore Inc. seems to have a =
trust bank, and Goldman, a bank holding company, has plenty of non-bank ent=
ities. The rough intuition =E2=80=9Cbig universal banks won=E2=80=99t be su=
bject to the rule, while boutique banks, hedge funds, proprietary trading f=
irms and asset managers will be=E2=80=9D is plausible but not certain, and =
as Sifma points out, =E2=80=9Cthe Proposed Rule also risks creating confusi=
on due to its potentially inconsistent application within banking organizat=
ions as some workers could be employed by segments outside the Commission=
=E2=80=99s jurisdiction while other workers could be employed by affiliate =
entities that the FTC believes are subject to the Proposed Rule.=E2=80=9D=
=20


  [6] Or frequent batch auctions lol.


  [7] The report begins by listing a bunch of =E2=80=9CU.S. Government Blac=
klists,=E2=80=9D starting with =E2=80=9CThe U.S. Department of the Treasury=
=E2=80=99s Non-Specially Designated National Chinese Military-Industrial Co=
mplex Companies List (NSCMIC List),=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Cbars U.S. perso=
ns from purchasing or selling publicly traded securities of designated enti=
ties, which support the PRC=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cmilitary, intelligence, and =
other security apparatuses.=E2=80=9D But later on it points out: =E2=80=9CF=
or the NS-CMIC List, its exposure to capital markets is entirely based on t=
he subsidiaries of listed companies because U.S. persons cannot trade secur=
ities issued by a designated company. They can, however, trade the securiti=
es of a designated company=E2=80=99s subsidiaries or affiliates.=E2=80=9D S=
o the investors buy the shares that they are allowed to buy, not the ones t=
hey aren=E2=80=99t allowed to buy. A footnote adds: =E2=80=9CSimilarly, nat=
ional security concerns do not meaningfully influence MSCI and BlackRock=E2=
=80=99s choices regarding index composition and fund creation. Companies ar=
e listed on the NS-CMIC List, which restricts investments in the companies=
=E2=80=99 publicly traded securities for military and human rights abuse ti=
es. When companies were removed from the NS-CMIC List, they became eligible=
 for inclusion in MSCI indexes at the next review, and they were added into=
 the indexes one to three months after they became eligible, despite the ri=
sks those companies pose to national security.=E2=80=9D Right: When they ar=
e on the banned list, they are not in the index! When they are *removed fro=
m the banned list*, then they get put in the index. If you don=E2=80=99t wa=
nt them in the index, leave them on the banned list!


