ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0after you quit.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Notice p=
eriods: When you start your job, you sign a contract saying that, if you wa=
nt to quit, you have to give six months=E2=80=99 advance notice. Then, when=
 you give notice, your employer says =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t even bother com=
ing to the office anymore, and we=E2=80=99re cutting you off email, but you=
 still work for us so you can=E2=80=99t work for a competitor.=E2=80=9D And=
 they keep paying you. (Often your base salary but not your bonus.)</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Deferred comp: Each year, your employer p=
ays you some cash and also some deferred pay, cash or stock or options or c=
arry that they hold onto for you and promise to deliver to you at some late=
r date. The terms of the deferred pay say that you can forfeit it in certai=
n circumstances. For instance, if you do a crime, or lose a bunch of money =
for the firm, they can claw back deferred pay that you earned in previous y=
ears. Often, if you leave the firm for a competitor, they can also claw it =
back.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Nondisclosure agreements (ND=
As): When you start your job, you sign a contract saying that all of the st=
uff you learn and do at the job is secret and belongs to your employer, and=
 that you are not allowed to disclose it to anyone else. And then when you =
quit, they say =E2=80=9Cjust so you know, if you go work at a competitor, w=
e=E2=80=99ll know that you=E2=80=99re using our secrets, and we=E2=80=99ll =
sue you.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The new FTC rule pr=
etty clearly bans No. 1, the explicit noncompete. But No. 2 is a common way=
 to do gardening leave, and I think it still works? The FTC says:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">With respect to garden leave agreements,=
 as noted previously, commenters used the term =E2=80=9Cgarden leave=E2=80=
=9D to refer to a wide variety of agreements. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0However, the C=
ommission notes that an agreement whereby the worker is still employed and =
receiving the same total annual compensation and benefits on a pro rata bas=
is would not be a non-compete clause under the definition, because such an =
agreement is not a post-employment restriction. Instead, the worker continu=
es to be employed, even though the worker=E2=80=99s job duties or access to=
 colleagues or the workplace may be significantly or entirely curtailed. Fu=
rthermore, where a worker does not meet a condition to earn a particular as=
pect of their expected compensation, like a prerequisite for a bonus, the C=
ommission would still consider the arrangement =E2=80=9Cgarden leave=E2=80=
=9D that is not a non-compete clause under this final rule even if the empl=
oyer did not pay the bonus or other expected compensation.=C2=A0</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That leaves some ambiguity about bonuses=
: Your gardening leave has to provide =E2=80=9Cthe same total annual compen=
sation=E2=80=9D as your regular job for it to be allowed, but if you do not=
 meet =E2=80=9Ca prerequisite for a bonus,=E2=80=9D they don=E2=80=99t have=
 to pay you the bonus. Presumably showing up to the office is a prerequisit=
e for your bonus, so I=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>this says that gardening le=
ave is still allowed as long as you are getting your normal base salary, wh=
ich can be quite a lot lower than your normal=C2=A0total annual compensatio=
n.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule=C2=A0also seems to ban=C2=A0No.=
 3, the clawback of deferred compensation for workers who leave for competi=
tors. The rule defines a =E2=80=9Cnon-compete clause=E2=80=9D to include =
=E2=80=9Ca term or condition of employment that prohibits a worker from,=C2=
=A0<em>penalizes a worker for</em>, or functions to prevent a worker from =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0seeking or accepting work=E2=80=9D at a competitor (emphasis=
 added). The FTC says:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another =
example of a term that =E2=80=9Cpenalizes=E2=80=9D a worker ... is an agree=
ment that extinguishes a person=E2=80=99s obligation to provide promised co=
mpensation or to pay benefits as a result of a worker seeking or accepting =
other work or starting a business after they leave their job. One example o=
f such an agreement is a forfeiture-for-competition clause, which, similar =
to the agreement with liquidated damages described previously, imposes adve=
rse financial consequences on a former employee as a result of the terminat=
ion of an employment relationship, expressly conditioned on the employee se=
eking or accepting other work or starting a business=C2=A0after their emplo=
yment ends.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here too there is =
some ambiguity. The way deferred compensation works at some financial firms=
