<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[7] The report begins by listing a bunch of =
=E2=80=9CU.S. Government Blacklists,=E2=80=9D starting with =E2=80=9CThe U.=
S. Department of the Treasury=E2=80=99s Non-Specially Designated National C=
hinese Military-Industrial Complex Companies List (NSCMIC List),=E2=80=9D w=
hich =E2=80=9Cbars U.S. persons from purchasing or selling publicly traded =
securities of designated entities, which support the PRC=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cmilitary, intelligence, and other security apparatuses.=E2=80=9D But lat=
er on it points out: =E2=80=9CFor the NS-CMIC List, its exposure to capital=
 markets is entirely based on the subsidiaries of listed companies because =
U.S. persons cannot trade securities issued by a designated company. They c=
an, however, trade the securities of a designated company=E2=80=99s subsidi=
aries or affiliates.=E2=80=9D So the investors buy the shares that they are=
 allowed to buy, not the ones they aren=E2=80=99t allowed to buy. A footnot=
e adds: =E2=80=9CSimilarly, national security concerns do not meaningfully =
influence MSCI and BlackRock=E2=80=99s choices regarding index composition =
and fund creation. Companies are listed on the NS-CMIC List, which restrict=
s investments in the companies=E2=80=99 publicly traded securities for mili=
